Relative to biological routes, thermochemical methods are more flexible and provide a simpler approach as there is no need for additional chemicals but instead heat and pressure are used to generate biofuels.43 This can be done by pyrolysis and/or gasification (Table 2).44,45 Gasification is a well-developed process where hydrogen-rich fuel gas (CO, H2, and CH4) is produced at 700–1200 °C using gasification agents (O2, CO2, steam, and air).16,20 Gasification with air produces a low-quality gas (4–7 MJ/m3 HHV), whereas higher quality gas (~10–18 MJ/m3 HHV) can be obtained under more oxidative conditions, i.e., pure O2.50 The gasification process using fluidized bed reactors have demonstrated high biomass conversion with H2 content in gas ~55 vol.% and H2 production of ~6.9 wt%.20,51 The cost of H2 production by gasification from biomass is estimated to be ~1.77–2.05 $/kg H2,14 and the process can be generalized in the following equation:52Table 2.
